Aim

To write a Python program to demonstrate tuple operations such as count, index, length, indexing, slicing, and conversion of a tuple into a list.

Algorithm

Start the program.
Create a tuple my_tuple with elements (10, 20, 30, 20, 40).
Print the tuple.
Use the count() method to count how many times the element 20 appears in the tuple.
Use the index() method to find the position of element 30 in the tuple.
Use the len() function to find the length of the tuple.
Access and print the first element of the tuple using index 0.
Access and print the last element of the tuple using index -1.
Perform slicing from index 1 to 3 (excluding 3) and print the result.
Convert the tuple into a list using the list() function.
Print the converted list.
Stop the program.

EXECUTE 
my_tuple = (10, 20, 30, 20, 40)

print("Tuple:", my_tuple)
print("Count 20:", my_tuple.count(20))
print("Index of 30:", my_tuple.index(30))
print("Length:", len(my_tuple))
print("First element:", my_tuple[0])
print("Last element:", my_tuple[-1])
print("Slicing:", my_tuple[1:3])

# Convert to list
my_list = list(my_tuple)
print("As list:", my_list)

OUTPUT
Tuple: (10, 20, 30, 20, 40)
Count 20: 2
Index of 30: 2
Length: 5
First element: 10
Last element: 40
Slicing: (20, 30)
As list: [10, 20, 30, 20, 40]
